          "body": "Two verses function as bookends for the entire chapter. Verse 12: 'Solomon sat on the throne of David his father, and his kingdom was firmly established.' Verse 46: 'Thus the kingdom was established in the hands of Solomon.' The same Hebrew root — kun, to be set firm — appears in both, and everything between them is the narrative of how the second statement became true. The envelope structure is a literary signal: the narrator is not presenting a series of political murders. He is presenting a unified theological argument. The four cases (Adonijah, Abiathar, Joab, Shimei) are not independent anecdotes; they are the constituent acts by which a divinely promised establishment becomes historically concrete. The chapter begins with a throne occupied and ends with a throne secured. What the first formula announces as an initial fact, the second formula confirms as an achieved reality."
