          "body": "The Adonijah episode (2:13-25) is the chapter's most psychologically complex case. Adonijah opens his conversation with Bathsheba with the word 'peacefully' (shalom), then proceeds to make a request that Solomon immediately reads as a disguised bid for the throne. The request is for Abishag the Shunammite, David's deathbed attendant and companion (1 Kings 1:1-4). In the ancient Near East, possession of a king's concubine or attendant was a recognized claim to succession — Absalom had publicly taken David's concubines precisely to signal his seizure of power (2 Samuel 16:21-22). Solomon's response is immediate and sharp: 'Ask for him also the kingdom' (2:22). The most telling detail is 2:15, where Adonijah himself says, 'the kingdom has turned about and become my brother's, for it was his from the LORD.' He confesses divine sovereignty and then, in the same breath, attempts to subvert it. Solomon's oath-verdict is not disproportionate — it is the logical consequence of a man who keeps reaching for a throne he has already acknowledged he has no right to hold."
