          "body": "Readers of 1 Kings 2 who know only this chapter will see a new king consolidating power. Readers who carry 2 Samuel 7, 1 Samuel 2, and Deuteronomy 17 into the text will see something larger: every promise and every curse God has spoken being executed with surgical precision across the chapter. The expulsion of Abiathar and the appointment of Zadok (2:35) fulfills the Shiloh oracle and establishes the Zadokite priestly line that will serve the temple Solomon will build in chapter 3. Joab's execution removes the last political shadow over David's bloodguilt — the man who had made himself David's enforcer and murderer is judged. Shimei's death closes the chapter opened at 2 Samuel 16 when David, fleeing Absalom, refused to answer a curse with a sword but promised it would be answered in God's timing. The chapter is a panorama of covenant faithfulness: not in the sense that all the characters behave faithfully, but in the sense that the God who makes promises keeps them, even when He keeps them through the hard instrument of royal justice."
